<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-442-236  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 442 236.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  May 10 1990 v35 n10 p55(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Handheld DMMs shine despite ill treatment. (digitalmultimeters)(includes related article on accuracy) (buyers guide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kerridge, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A guide to hand-held digital multimeters (DMMs) is presented.andP;  Abasic instrument comprehensively covering voltage, current, andresistance measurement costs as little as $99; ruggedized,electrically-robust units cost approximately $290.andP;  Defenses fromelectrical overload prolong the life of a DMM, and many modelstoday can now protect against stabs of up to 1,200 volts.andP;  Mostmodels have an impedance of 10 mega-ohms.andP;  Beckman Industries, HP,and others offer models they claim to be drop-proof and waterresistant.andP;  Potential buyers should note a DMM's accuracy whenmonitoring both direct and alternating current.andP;  Analog displaysare better than digital ones in some situations; they allow theuser to view trends more effectively.andP;  Some DMMs featuretemperature measurement.andP;  All should be re-calibrated once a yearfor accuracy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Test EquipmentIntegrated circuitsCircuit DesignAnalog SystemsDirectoriesMeasurementMetersVoltage.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Representative handheld DMMs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>